      • toNonEmptyOrThrow

        Returns a NonEmptySet containing the same elements as this one, if this Set is not empty. Use this if you are confident that this Set is not empty.

        If this Set is empty, throws an IllegalArgumentException.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

      • wrap

        static <A> Set<A> wrap(java.util.Set<A> underlying)
        Wraps a Set in a Set.

        Does *not* make a copy of the given Set. The Set will hold a reference to the underlying Set, but will not alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this Set will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying data, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the underlying data, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to it the underlying Set can still mutate it.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        underlying - Set to wrap
        Returns:
        a Set<A>

      • copyFrom

        static <A> ImmutableSet<A> copyFrom(java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableSet from any Iterable.

        The entire Iterable will be eagerly iterated, so be careful not to pass in an infinite Iterable or this method will not terminate.

        If necessary to guarantee immutability, this method will make a copy of the data provided. If source already is an ImmutableSet, it will be returned directly.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly in its entirety
        Returns:
        an ImmutableSet<A>

      • copyFrom

        static <A> ImmutableSet<A> copyFrom(int maxCount,
                                    java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableSet from any Iterable, but consuming a maximum number of elements.

        The Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only up to a maximum of maxCount elements. If maxCount elements are not available, then the all of the elements available will be returned.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, unless source is an ImmutableSet and its size is less than or equal to maxCount, in which case it will be returned directly.

        If source is an ImmutableSet that is greater than maxCount in size, a copy will always be made, therefore making it memory-safe to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        maxCount - the maximum number of elements to consume from the source. Must be >= 0.
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly for up to maxCount elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableSet that contains at most maxCount elements.
